The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that election irregularities would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout all of southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terrorism.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe have been victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
ZANU terrorism is attributable to the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The consequence of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas.
Moreover, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, especially in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Because there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, unable to cast their ballot.
I continue to doubt the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from placing observers at 52% of the rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the voting, our party was missing observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the rural areas.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will at these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
Even at this early stage of our investigations, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most of the votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president, Robert Mugabe, emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is therefore illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe were deprived of their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The struggle over the election results is a political issue that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were courageous and determined and deserve to be acknowledged for this.
Perhaps it is not yet too late for this.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to its end.
Perhaps the government wants to arrest me.
I was also arrested for treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will to reclaim their rights and power.
It is in our hands to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
Political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger of the news.
Should that happen, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to remain strong and see through to the end what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who would not be sent away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together in order to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people has rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve loveableness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply leave these elections as they are, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African states, irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always a crisis somewhere because of elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to dishonest means when it is time to grant the people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I pledge not to leave them.
